Lens Flare
Motivation
  • The human eye does not suffer from this artifact
  • However, mechanical cameras do
    • Light bouncing around inside the lenses
    • People often expect to see this effect
    • We want to simulate it
Example
  • Example: Link
Procedure
  • First, render the scene to the screen as usual
    • No difference from what we’ve done already
  • Next, we need to add the glare effects
  • We need to know where (on the screen) the light source is located
    • Fortunately, we have everything we need…
Light Source
  • Let L = world space location of light source
  • Compute:
    • S = L * viewMatrix * projMatrix
    • S = 1.0/S.w * S
  • Note: The camera holds the view and projection matrices
  • S is screen space location of light source (in GL’s -1…1 coordinates)
Procedure
  • Draw a quad centered around S textured with a glow texture (usually a soft radial gradient)
  • Use additive blending
    • glBlendFunc( GL_SRC_ALPHA, GL_ONE );
Code
  • Sketch of CPU side code:
glBlendFunc(GL_SRC_ALPHA, GL_ONE);
flareProg->use();
Program::setUniform("worldMatrix",translation(S.x,S.y,0));
glowTexture->bind(0);
fullscreenquad.draw();
glBlendFunc(GL_SRC_ALPHA, GL_ONE_MINUS_SRC_ALPHA);
VS
  • The vertex shader doesn’t have too much to do…
layout(location=0) in vec3 position;
layout(location=1) in vec2 texcoord;
out vec2 v_texcoord;
void main(){
    vec4 p = vec4(position,1.0);
    p = p * worldMatrix;
    gl_Position = p;
    v_texcoord = texcoord;
}
  • Notice: We don’t use view or projection matrices
  • We do use world matrix so we can scale or translate
FS
  • Very simple FS
layout(binding=0) uniform sampler2DArray tex;
in vec2 v_texcoord;
out vec4 color;
void main(){
    vec4 c = texture(tex,vec3(v_texcoord,0.0));
    color=c;
}
  • Just pull data from texture and output it
Artifacts
  • Next, we want to add the multiple-bounce artifacts
  • Usually, these have shapes like hexagons, rings, or maybe circles
  • Where to position these?
Artifacts
  • We have S: light position in screen space
  • Consider a line (in screen space) throuh (0,0) and S
  • Draw several screen aligned quads of various size along this line at various positions
Procedure
  • Let t = some value (usually between -2 and 2)
    • 0 = at S
    • 1 = at center of screen
  • Compute q = S - tS
  • Draw quad centered around q:
    • Set worldMatrix to scale & translate
    • Scale amount is arbitrary…Try different values to find some good ones
  • Example:
    Program::setUniform(“worldMatrix”, scaling(scaleAmt) * translation(q) );
Example
  • I used textures like so
  • This would look better if the flare sprites had color modulation instead of being monochromatic
Values
  • I used these values:
Texture t scale Texture t scale Texture t scale
1 -0.6 0.1 2 -0.1 0.14 3 -0.4 0.06
0.25 0.05 0.3 0.2 0.4 0.04
1.1 0.15 0.5 0.1 0.7 0.08
1.7 0.3 1.2 0.16
Problem
  • Even if the light source is offscreen (i.e., behind the viewer or off the edge), the flares are still drawn
Solution
  • We need to look at the coordinates in S
  • When x or y coordinate reaches 0.9, start fading to zero; fade out completely when coordinate is 1.2
    • Why 0.9 and 1.2?
      • S is location of light source center
      • But light source has nonzero width
  • Also, if z indicates it’s behind the viewer, don’t draw it
Procedure
  • CPU side code:
S = lightPos * viewMatrix;
if( S.z > 0 )
    alphaScale = 0.0;
else{
    S = S * projMatrix;
    S *= 1.0/S.w;
    float tmp = max(fabs(S.x),fabs(S.y));
    const float fadeStart = 0.9;
    const float fadeEnd = 1.2;
    float alphaScale = 1.0-(tmp-fstart)/(fend-fstart);
    ...clamp alphaScale to 0...1...
}
FS
  • Now modify the flare fragment shader:
  • CPU code has set the uniform alphaScale
layout(binding=0) uniform sampler2DArray tex;
in vec2 v_texcoord;
out vec4 color;
void main(){
    vec4 c = texture(tex,vec3(v_texcoord,0.0));
    color = c;
    color.a *= alphaScale;
}
Analyis
  • This partially fixes our problem
  • But: What happens if light source is occluded by objects?
    • We still see flare
Solution
  • Create a second camera (called “suncamera”):
  • Same eye point as ordinary camera
  • Center of interest = light position
  • Field of view very narrow
    • Sun is only 0.5° wide
    • I used 6° for my camera
  • Create another FBO
  • Can be fairly small
    • I used 16x16
  • Call this “sunfbo”
Draw
  • Our draw code now looks like this:
    • Draw ordinary scene as usual
sunfbo->setAsRenderTarget(true);  //clear it to black
sunCamera->setUniforms();
glColorMask(false,false,false,false);
...draw scene, except light source...
glColorMask(true,true,true,true);
...draw geometry representing light source...
sunfbo->unsetAsRenderTarget()
Result
  • Color mask + first draw: Sets depth buffer but leaves color buffer black
  • Second draw: Sets pixels of color buffer where sun is not obscured by object
    • Assumes sun has an emission map
    • Thus, its pixels will be fairly bright
Result
  • Sunfbo will have white pixels wherever sun was visible, black where not visible
  • The more sun that is visible, the more white pixels in sunfbo
Next
  • Need to count number of white pixels
  • Easy: Just use the highest mipmap level of sunfbo (1x1 pixel)
    • The whiter it is, the more sun pixels are visible
Render
  • Send sunfbo texture to the flare shader program as another texture input
    • subfbo->texture->bind(1);
  • Set blend mode as described previously and draw the glow + flare artifacts
FS
  • Flare fragment shader will use sunfbo to scale brightness
layout(binding=0) uniform sampler2DArray tex;
layout(binding=1) uniform sampler2DArray suntex
in vec2 v_texcoord;
out vec4 color;
void main(){
    //get base flare color
    vec4 c = texture(tex,vec3(v_texcoord,0.0));
    //get highest mip level = average color
    float a = texture(suntex, vec3(v_texcoord,0.0),999.0).r;
    color=c;
    //modulate by light source visibility
    color.a *= alphaScale * a;
}
Note
  • It seems like you shouldn’t need to use v_texcoord on the ‘float a’ line in the FS
  • But on my machine, it always sampled mip level 0 when I used a constant vec3 in texture()
